git hub :

""" In git hub repository if you fork a repo by deafult you are on master branch.
 To commit changes on git hub below steps are mendatory """
For existing Project:
    I. Fork A Repo:
A fork is a copy of a repository. Forking a repository allows you to freely experiment with changes without affecting the original project.
Refer this link for exact steps:
https://help.github.com/articles/fork-a-repo

    II.Clone the git repo on your system local repo
For example forked a sos repository:https://github.com/sosreport/sos to clone use below command:

$ git clone https://github.com/sosreport/sos

Add and modify the patches for example "python.py" patch (commit and push to test branch then merge in the master branch for sosreport)

Since this sosreport go through the contributor guidelines: https://github.com/sosreport/sos/wiki/Contribution-Guidelines

    III.Syncing a fork
    Now before merging the changes keep  syncing the local repository with the upstream refer steps:
    A) Configure a remote for fork with original project link:refer steps in
https://help.github.com/articles/configuring-a-remote-for-a-fork

    B)Syncing a fork with your project:
fetch the  upstream repository refer steps in
https://help.github.com/articles/syncing-a-fork

    IV. Pushing changes to remote:
    To push the changes made on your local branch to remote use  below command:

    git push  <REMOTENAME> <BRANCHNAME> 
eg:usually run git push origin master to push your local changes to your online repository.
https://help.github.com/articles/pushing-to-a-remote#pushing-a-branch

https://help.github.com/articles/dealing-with-non-fast-forward-errors

https://help.github.com/articles/fetching-a-remote


    V.Using pull requests:
Pull requests let you tell others about changes you've pushed to a GitHub repository. Once a pull request is sent, interested parties can review the set of changes, discuss potential modifications, and even push follow-up commits if necessary.
For details on pull request:
https://help.github.com/articles/using-pull-requests
